title: For Sale:  1971 M35A2 Deuce
postcontent:
This truck has a Continental, non-whistler 6 cylinder turbo diesel engine with a 5 speed transmission and two speed air shifted transfer case. The j-pipe for the exhaust is 100% stainless and will not rust out. About 24k miles and 966 hours as it is still being driven, the truck was rebuilt in 1989. I have added spin-on oil filters and secondary fuel filters.   Both batteries have been replaced in April of last year. The cargo cover had a rip in it, was fixed and from the outside you can hardly tell. I bought the truck from Joe Czarnick in Appleton WI a little over 5 years ago. He had just sandblasted the truck and painted it with CARC paint and it looks as good today as it did the day that I bought it. The spare tire is a 11.00-20 Michelin XL, as is the extra mounted spare that is in the bed. When I bought this truck it was running singles. I did all of the work to return it to duals. The truck does have a cab heater and I recently replaced the in tank fuel pump with a 24 volt inline unit. Both front inner axle seals have been changed and the differential was drained and refilled. Over the last year I have had all the wheels off at one time or another and the brakes are in excellent shape yet. The front tires are G177’s as is one tire on the rear, the rest are G188’s. All of the rubber rope for the cargo cover has been replaced. I also built a 2" receiver hitch for it.
I will sell just the truck with the cargo cover for $5900

 The Zastava EZ 40 is a modern weapon used as a service gun or a personal defense gun. Due to excellent design solutions, ergonomics, state-of-the art technology in production, this weapon stands out with its precision, accuracy and functionality. The design is a semi-automatic weapon, functioning on the short recoil of the barrel principle. Locking is achieved by vertical oscillation of the barrel, that comes into the hole on the slide. title: For Sale:  .177 Side Cock Air Rifle - Solid Steel and Wood
location: Bolton, VT (20 minutes from Burlington), Vermont, United States
postcontent:
QB 88 Chinese Air Rifle.  Nothing fancy – but a rugged, solidly built side-cocker that works great for small game and pest control without alerting the neighbors.  The wood is finished nicely for a Chinese product, and the steel is good quality.  

Comes with a scope (came with the gun).  I’ve used the iron sites, which while a pain to adjust, did get me a good group.  I have not mounted or tried the scope.  It has a clear field of vision and looks surprisingly good.  

Included with the air gun is the original owner’s manual and a tin of pellets (not full, but enough to get you started).  

Guns of this quality usually sell for around 75.00-100.00 new (Tech Force imports similar Chinese guns).  

This gun was manufactured in 1998, my father bought it new during the summer of ’99, and I’d guess it never saw more than 100 rounds through it.  

I’m asking $50.00, which is more than fair, so I won’t dicker.  This is a very good gun for the money, and I’m sure you’ll be hard pressed to find a better quality gun for this money anywhere.  

Let me know if you’re interested in looking at it – thank you for checking this ad.

title: For Sale:  Burris 3-9X-40 Fullfield II Ballistic Plex Riflescope AND 10X-32mm Landmark Binocular
postcontent:
BRAND NEW in factory sealed package. Scope by itself retails for $200, so you're basically getting the binoculars for free (which retail for $115). Willing to ship for $15.00 extra.

Burris 3-9x40mm Fullfield II Rifle Scope w/ Burris 10x32mm Landmark Binoculars gives you a full spot-and-shoot package! This value package from Burris includes the Burris 3x-9x 40mm Fullfield-II Riflescope and the Burris Landmark 10x32mm Binoculars.

The Burris Fullfield II Rifle Scope has a one-piece main tube and eyepiece, Burris envied steel-on-steel adjustment system, and HiLume multi-coatings on every single air to glass lens surface. The Burris FullField-II Scope is even more forgiving for eye position, is a little shorter, and a good bit lighter. The magnification ring and eyepiece have been made into one solid unit requiring only two seals rather than three. To change magnification, simply turn the entire eyepiece. Burris Fullfield 2 Scope eliminated most of the potential leak paths in the eyepiece/power ring area and sealed the remainder with special quad seals instead of O-rings. The adjustment system has been moved to improve mounting options and the European-style adjustable eyepiece requires no locking mechanism. The Ballistic Plex reticle has a lower vertical crosshair with small ballistic lines that automatically compensate for bullet drop from 100 to 500 yards for many common cartridges. The Burris Fullfield-2 Riflescope is lighter, better sealed, and has a relocated adjustment system compared to the original Burris Fullfield.

The Burris Landmark Binoculars combine light weight, fully coated lenses and water resistant, fogproof construction. These Burris Binoculars also include a tough rubber armor coating and twist-up eyecups. Top all this off with a neck strap, carrying case, a full year warranty and a very affordable price and you have yourself a synonym for optical value.

Specifications for Burris 3-9x40 Fullfield II Rifle Scope:

Adjustable Objective: No

Features of Burris 3-9x40mm Fullfield II Rifle Scope:

Waterproof: All Burris optics are proven to be absolutely waterproof. Each scope is submerged in water with a temperature of 50° C. The extremely hot water transfers its heat to the scope and the internal nitrogen expends 100% testing assures quality. Each scope is filled and purged at least 24 times with high quality, laboratory grade dry nitrogen. Each nitrogen cycle absorbs airborne and residual surface moisture that is evacuated from the scope. Burris uses specially made quad seals to provide double insurance against leakage.
Fog proof: The nitrogen contained in the scope is of high quality (ultra dry, laboratory grade nitrogen), ultra pure and ultra clean. To be sure that all airborne moisture and surfaces moisture within a scope is evacuated, testing consists of 24 cycles of pressurizing the scope and then subjecting it to a vacuum. The tests are both cost & time intensive.
Shock proof: Burris scopes are subjected to extreme recoil tests. An impact machine is used to measure and duplicate the recoil pulse acceleration and duration. This machine has been calibrated and verified by an independent laboratory to replicate the wave frequencies and shock impulses that a scope is subjected to.
Ballistic Plex reticle - with a basic crosshair reticle, calculating hold-over is a mix of art, science and just plain luck, which is why Burris developed the Ballistic Plex reticle. The key is the copyrighted lower vertical crosshair. With most common hunting cartridges, a shooter can use the reticle to compensate for bullet drop and aim dead-on at targets from 100 to 500 yards out. The need for hold-over guesstimation is eliminated. Using it is simple. Start by sighting-in your rifle at 100 or 200 yards at your scope's highest magnification. Then, once you determine the distance to your target, select the appropriate ballistic line. Add slight hold-over or hold-under for in-between yardages and take the shot.

title: For Sale:  S&W Smith & Wesson 396 Night Guard 44 Spl
postcontent: Very Nice Looks to be in as new condition with it's original box with all the original paperwork. That is not a scratch above the cylinder release thumb piece. It is a factory arrow showing which way to turn the lock key and is on all 396s. I don't know anyone who locks a gun. Rare S&W 396 .44 spl. These guns were made a very short time only due to the unpopularity of the caliber at the time. Everyone wanted the .44 Mag. at the time. Now they are popular and hard to find. The 396 I'm told was made for only 9 months. I called S&W and they have no plans to make more. Most people don't know that S&W made a .44 Spl on the L frame and as the word gets out these guns will become even more sought after and very rare. Try to find another one for sale even now. Those who do have one like it too much to sell. You lucked out to find this one for sale. I like that the 396 NG .44 Spl. has a steel barrel and steel cylinder unlike the other S&W Night Guard models which have alloy cylinders. I have a 396 and a 696 that I shoot and can verify they are fantastic weapons that I won't be without.

title: For Sale:  Barrett M107A1 20" CQ 50 BMG Guncrafter 50GI
postcontent:
This item is new, we are a licensed gun shop and we received it from the manufacturer or a distributor. It has never been fired and since our shop specializes in more expensive, higher end merchandise we are not open to the public. This usually means you will get a pristine, mint condition example that has never been handled by anybody as most of our inventory is received and shipped out in the same box it arrived in and never even opened.

BARRETT M107A1 !!

The Barrett M107A1 .50 BMG semi-automatic rifle is an exceptional firearm! Here are some of the new upgrades:

* It has the upgraded muzzle brake which gives you less recoil, and enables you to stay on target for faster, more accurate follow up shots. The new 4 chamber muzzlebrake is also able to receive their quick attach suppressor if you ever wanted to silence your 50. (Barrett has said that currently the new muzzlebrake is not available as a separate accessory for the M82A1).

* It's made of a much stronger, lighter titanium, so even though it's very light it's more durable, and the titanium w/ the upgraded brake keeps recoil down. Also aluminum and steel areas where possible have been thinned for further weight savings without sacrificing the integrity of the design.

* The mags are much better with a tougher finish, and the mag has sight holes so you can tell exactly how many rounds you have left; our customers that hunt w/ their .50's love that feature, and our troops demand it.

* The finish on the M107's is much more durable, scratch resistant and rust resistant.

* It has the thermal cheek guard that allows the shooter to rest their face on the cheek plate and not directly on metal. Also, it's elevated which is ideal because the M107A1 has a really long, elevated mono-rail.

* It has a lightweight, quick detach bipod with modular feet.

* It has a monopod as standard equipment instead of having to pay additional and add as an accessory; this is a big help so you do not have to support the weight of the rear of the rifle with your own strength. It also allows you to dial the elevation of where your aiming up or down with the monopod with even more accuracy so even if you don't want to upgrade you may want to ask about adding a monopod.

*The case it comes with from the factory is an upgrade from a Pelican case to a nicer Storm case. The Storm case is much easier to open and close, and you don’t bust your knuckles on it, and the case features padding inside instead of bare plastic.

*More potential investment value as it has the same rollmark as our military gets, with the M107A1 designation. We see with our Knights Armament Rifles, Schmidt & Bender scopes, Remington Defense rifles, etc. that military markings always drive up price further down the road when the rifles are no longer offered.

FROM BARRETT:

It may be related to the Model M82A1, but the M107A1 is far from a simple evolution. Driven by the demands of combat, every component was re-engineered to be lighter yet stronger. The result? A high-performance rifle that weighs four pounds less than the original M107, but is every bit as tough.

Designed to be used with a suppressor, this one-of-a-kind rifle allows you to combine signature reduction capabilities with the flawless reliability of the original Barrett® M107. An all-new bolt carrier group has been designed that is key to making the rifle suppressor-ready. its titanium four-port muzzle brake is engineered to work seamlessly with a quick-attach Barrett .50 BMG Suppressor.

The lightweight aluminum upper receiver features an integrated, rigid 27 MOA optics rail. Inside the upper receiver, the bolt carrier rides on a hardened steel, anti-wear strip for added durability. A thermal-guard cheek piece protects the user’s face from extreme heat or cold.

Advanced design and manufacturing make the M107A1 more precise than ever. The rear-barrel stop and front-barrel bushing are bolted and bonded with a compound similar to that used on space shuttles. A titanium barrel key and fully chrome-lined bore and chamber add to the rifle’s durability.

Enhanced modularity is also a key feature. The rifle’s rail-mounted aluminum rear grip can easily be reconfigured. The newly designed titanium and polymer monopod is easily adjustable from either side. The M107A1 rifle’s lower receiver includes a new aluminum recoil buffer system that’s optimized for use with a suppressor. The bolt carrier’s components are protected with a mix of ultra-hard PVD coatings and advanced nickel Teflon® plating that increases lubricity, is corrosion-resistant and greatly eases cleaning.

Numbered witness holes on the magazine are just another example of how even the smallest detail makes a powerful difference.

Features:

Suppressor-ready muzzle brake. Lightweight quick-detach bipod with modular feet. Accepts M1913 accessory rails. Thermal cheek guard. Modular hand-grip mounted on M1913 rail. Model:M107A1 Caliber:.50 BMG Operation:Semi-Automatic Rifling Twist:1 turn in 15” (38.1 cm) Magazine Capacity:10 Rounds

NIGHTFORCE NXS 5.5-22X56 MOAR ILLUMINATED!!

The Nightforce NXS 5.5-22x56 tactical scope gives the shooter a broad magnification range, four inches of eye relief and 100 MOA of elevation travel. This NXS retains a slim profile and is easily adaptable to a wide range of mounting systems.

Nightforce uses outstanding glass and coatings in all their scopes, and the 5.5-22x50 tactical gives you superb resolution at high magnifications. It is the ultimate long range scope. The 50mm objective lens gives you maximum clarity and resolution across the entire magnification range. This Nightforce scope gives the shooter precision accuracy at the longest ranges, yet at 5.5 power remains highly effective for shots at close ranges.

The MOAR reticle is an improved, more versatile version of the NP-R1 reticle. The MOAR has subtensions that are thicker than those of NF’s traditional reticles, which makes the reticle easier to see against dark backgrounds. The MOAR has 1 MOA spacing on the horizontal and vertical axis’, and this is a great tool for precise range-finding and hold offs. The first hash marks on the reticle are 2 MOA from center, and the crosshair is 1 MOA in length.

The new MOAR reticle has a floating center crosshair, and it allows shooters to bracket the target by using the box created by the first MOA lines. Plus, the MOAR reticle’s simplicity enables the shooter to rely more on the reticle than on constant turret adjustments.

From Nightforce:

Originally developed for the U.S. military’s extreme long range shooting and hard target interdiction, both 5.5-22 Nightforce NXS models provide a broad magnification range, four inches of eye relief and 100 MOA of elevation travel. These characteristics, combined with the extreme ruggedness and reliability of every Nightforce riflescope, make them ideal for even the largest calibers. The slim profile of the 5.5-22 x 56 NXS makes it easily adaptable to a wide range of mounting systems. Its superb resolution at high magnification opens an entirely new world of extended range shooting for the accomplished marksman; Nightforce shooters are now accurately reaching to 2000 yards and beyond.

title: For Sale:  S&W Smith & Wesson 396 Night Guard 44 Spl
postcontent: Very Nice Looks to be in as new condition with it's original box with all the original paperwork. That is not a scratch above the cylinder release thumb piece. It is a factory arrow showing which way to turn the lock key and is on all 396s. I don't know anyone who locks a gun. Rare S&W 396 .44 spl. These guns were made a very short time only due to the unpopularity of the caliber at the time. Everyone wanted the .44 Mag. at the time. Now they are popular and hard to find. The 396 I'm told was made for only 9 months. I called S&W and they have no plans to make more. Most people don't know that S&W made a .44 Spl on the L frame and as the word gets out these guns will become even more sought after and very rare. Try to find another one for sale even now. Those who do have one like it too much to sell. You lucked out to find this one for sale. I like that the 396 NG .44 Spl. has a steel barrel and steel cylinder unlike the other S&W Night Guard models which have alloy cylinders. I have a 396 and a 696 that I shoot and can verify they are fantastic weapons that I won't be without.
